I have only a few minutes right now, but I wanted to honor both Cook and Ed with a response to their posts above. I hope to have some more time to come back and post a longer message in the next day or so.<br><br>
I put the messages in a &quot;holding area&quot; (I haven't deleted them) not to &quot;protect&quot; one person.  In fact, Ed, the first of the 110 messages I removed from #20 was yours -- an all out attack on Spatz that, as far as I could see, was unprovoked (at least in terms of what he'd been posting there recently).  <br><br>
I don't know you Ed, and I haven't been able to read many of the threads over the past few months so I don't know very much more about you than the messages you and I exchanged privately a few weeks ago.  But I see you as an eloquent, poetic and pretty reasonable person *except* when you're talking about Spatz, when you really seem to be in a rage.<br><br>
Cook's messages on #20 were also very intense (to use a mild word).  I spent a few hours reading over the whole exchange last night, and there was nothing in all 110 posts about issues or ideas -- it was all about people hurling insults and degrading language at each other, trying to hurt each other.  Yes, it's part of reality.  But frankly I felt that putting that stuff back up would just remind everybody how pissed off they are and we'd be off and running again.<br><br>
Please tell me I'm wrong, Ed.  Do you want to spend all of your time on this site hunting Spatz down and denouncing him, or do you want to move on to the point where you can learn something from your brothers and maybe even from people you disagree with?  <br><br>
To me, putting the stuff up from #20 is an invitation for everybody to be their worst selves all over again.  I didn't take it down to protect Spatz, I took it down to try to preserve the integrity of the site.  But I'm willing to be told I made a mistake and I'm willing to change my mind.  That's why I created thread #186. 
